{{Infobox artist | name = Abraham Jacobus Wendel | image = Abraham Jacobus Wendel (Leiden, 31 October 1826 - Leiden, 23 September 1915) - botanical illustrator.jpg | caption = | birth_name = Abraham Jacobus Wendel | birth_date = {{birth date|df=yes|1826|10|31}} | birth_place = [[Leiden]] | death_date = {{death date and age|df=yes|1915|9|23|1826|10|31}} | death_place = Leiden | field = lithography, botanical art | movement = | works = | signature = }} [[File:Abraham Jacobus Wendel - Viola tricolor- 2.jpg|thumb|''Viola tricolor'' by A.J. Wendel]] [[File:Abraham Jacobus Wendel - Hibiscus syriacus Linn. - Chromolithograph.jpg|thumb|''Hibiscus syriacus'' L. by A.J. Wendel]] '''Abraham Jacobus Wendel''' ([[Leiden]], 31 October 1826 - Leiden, 23 September 1915) was a Dutch [[lithographer]], [[draughtsman]] and scientific [[Botanical illustrator|botanical]] and [[paleontology| paleontological]] [[illustrator]] using the signature AW.<ref name=rkd>[https://rkd.nl/en/explore/artists/110212 Abraham Jacobus Wendel] in Dutch [[RKD]]</ref>
== Life and work == Abraham Jacobus Wendel was born in 1826 in Leiden as a son of Jacobus Cornelis Wendel (1796-1860) and Johanna Vegt (1801-1869). In 1849 he married Jannetje Koolen (1826-1904) and had six children, including Abraham Jacobus Johannes Wendel (Leiden, 9 July 1854 - 3 April 1930),<ref name=genea>[https://www.myheritage.nl/person-3000619_182835582_182835582/abraham-jacobus-wendel Abraham Jacobus Wendel] in myheritage.com</ref><ref>[https://www.erfgoedleiden.nl/collecties/personen/zoek-op-personen/q/custom_text_persoon/Abraham%20Jacobus%20Johannes%20Wendel Erfgoedleiden.nl Abraham Jacobus Johannes Wendel]</ref> who became a lithographer and botanical artist in his own right, using signature AJJW. His father Abraham Jacobus Wendel created the botanical illustrations for many books and scientific journal articles. He was a lithographer with the printing house ''Arntz & Co.'' in Leiden, and made the illustrations for W. H. De Vriese et al. ''Descriptions et figures des plantes nouvelles et rares'' (1847). In 1887 he worked with ''Boek- en steendrukkerij P.W.M. Trap'' in Leiden: both Wendel and Trap are acknowledged in volumes 6 and 7 of the ''Annales du [[Bogor Botanical Gardens|Jardin botanique de Buitenzorg]]'' (Ann.Jard.Bot.Btzg.).<ref>Database [[National Herbarium of the Netherlands]] (NHN, Naturalis Biodiversity Center), refer to [[w:c:List of artists in Category:Icones art collection at Naturalis Biodiversity Center|List of artists in Category:Icones art collection at Naturalis Biodiversity Center]]</ref>
