'''Boris Rtcheouloff / Rcheulishvili''' ({{lang-ka|'''ბორის რჩეულიშვილი'''}}) was a [[Georgia (country)|Georgian]] [[scientist]], and the [[inventor]] of “[[videotape]]”.<ref>US Consumer Electronics Industry Today (Consumer Electronics Manufacturers Association, 1999)</ref> Early attempts to record television signals on magnetic material had started when Boris Rtcheouloff applied for a [[United Kingdom|British]] [[patent]] on [[January 1927|4 January 1927]]<ref>Paul McDonald, ''Video and DVD industries'' (British Film Institute, 22 Jan 2008) p.20</ref> for a technique of [[Video recording|recording]] [[television]] signals on 'a magnetic record of the [[Valdemar Poulsen|Poulsen]] telegraphone type'.<ref>George Shiers and May Shiers, ''Early Television: A Bibliographic Guide to 1940'' (Taylor and Francis, 1997) p.69</ref> [[Sound]] would be recorded in sync on the reverse side. These ideas incorporated a way to record sound or pictures by causing a strip, disc, or cylinder of iron or other [[magnet]]ic material to be magnetized. He did not pay the annual renewal fee, so his patent soon lapsed.<ref>New Scientist, (Vol. 100, No. 1386, Dec 1983) p.666</ref>

His godfather is the renowned opera singer [[Feodor Chaliapin]]<ref>[http://www.computer-museum.ru/connect/tvrechis.htm] "Из истории магнитной видеозаписи", Computer Museum, Authors: Н. В. Дунаевская, В. А. Урвалов, М. Г. Шульман</ref>

