{{Unreferenced|date=December 2009}}
'''Digger gold''' is the common slang term {{Citation needed|date=February 2012}} for [[gold]] recovered from electronics components such as board fingers, [[CPU]]s, and connector pins.
== Methods ==
For the gold fingers on boards or [[Electronic circuit|circuits]], often a stripping solution is used to remove the gold from the board material; [[nitric acid]] also works well in this regard as many gold components are soldered to boards with silver-based solders that are soluble in nitric acid (which gold is not). After dissolving all other metals in solution, the digger gold is recovered by dissolution of the gold in [[aqua regia]] and subsequent selective [[Precipitation (chemistry)|precipitation]] of the gold using [[ferrous sulfate]] or another selective [[reducing agent]] such as [[hydrazine]].
== See also ==
* [[Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive]] * [[eDay]] * [[Computer recycling]] * [[E-Cycling]]
