{{Infobox scientist | name = Paul Adams | image = <!--please insert--> | image_size = 200 px | caption = | birth_date = | birth_place = | residence = [[United States]] | nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]] | field = [[Biology|Biologist]], [[Neuroscience|neuroscientist]] | work_institution = [[State University of New York at Stony Brook]] | alma_mater = [[Cambridge University]] | doctoral_advisor = Juan Quilliam | doctoral_students = | known_for = | prizes = <!--please insert--> | religion = | footnotes = }}
'''Paul Richard Adams''', [[Royal Society|FRS]] is a neuroscientist currently serving as a Professor in the Department of Neurobiology and Behavior at [[Stony Brook University]] in [[New York (state)|New York]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://neurobiology.informatics.sunysb.edu/graduate/faculty/adams.html |title=Paul R. Adams Professor |accessdate=28 October 2010 }}</ref>
He graduated from [[London University]] with a PhD, and postdoctoral work with [[Bert Sakmann]] at the [[Max Planck Institute]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pharm.stonybrook.edu/adams |title=Paul Adams, PhD - Professor, Neurobiology and Behavior |accessdate=28 October 2010 |deadurl=yes |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100611182505/http://www.pharm.stonybrook.edu/adams |archivedate=11 June 2010 |df= }}</ref> He won the Novartis Memorial Prize in 1979 and the Gaddum Memorial Award in 1984, both from the British Pharmacological Society. He was made an [[MacArthur Fellows Program|MacArthur Foundation Prize Fellow]] in 1986, and elected as a [[Royal Society|Fellow of the Royal Society]] in 1991. From 1987 to 1995 he was an investigator at the [[Howard Hughes Medical Institute]].
With others, he pioneered the concepts of open channel block and [[Neuromodulation (biology)|neuromodulation]], which now play central roles in neuroscience. He is now working on a theory about the neocortex, centering on the idea that the key to sophisticated learning is extremely specific synaptic strength adjustment.
==Patents== *[http://www.faqs.org/patents/app/20080294580 Neuromorphic Device for Proofreading Connection Adjustments in Hardware Artificial Neural Networks]
